  "opinion": "As an 85-year-old woman living in Chicago, retired and spending several hours daily on social media, I've seen how fake content can stir up anxiety and confusion, especially for someone like me with a moderate level of neuroticism. Managing this issue requires a blend of caution and community effort. First, I always take a moment to pause before sharing anything online. My lower secondary education taught me to question things, and I rely on trusted sources like local news or family members to verify information. Given my anxious nature, I avoid sensational posts that play on fears, focusing instead on uplifting content from my hobbies like photography and hiking groups. I also use social media's reporting features when I spot fake news, as my moderate agreeableness drives me to help others avoid misinformation. In my Hindu faith, truth is sacred, so I strive to uphold honesty online. I discuss posts with my husband and children, who often guide me, leveraging their experiences. While my low conscientiousness means I'm not always meticulous, I've learned to set boundaries, limiting my time on platforms that spread falsehoods. Ultimately, dealing with fake content is about staying connected to real-life relationships and using social media as a tool for joy, not distress.",
